      "body" : "@Snicolas: I did.  However, you can&#39;t do this by calling <code>setAccessible</code> on the constructor as the <code>AccessibleObject.setAccessible</code> method explicitly checks you&#39;re not trying to make the <code>Class</code> constructor accessible and throws a SecurityException if you are.  You have to make the <code>override</code> field in <code>AccessibleObject</code> accessible and then set that to <code>true</code> in order to make the <code>Class</code> constructor accessible.  The exception I mentioned is what you get if you try to call the Class constructor once you have made it accessible."
